MPL.AX 12m Price Target: A\\$4.80 Price: A\\$5.02 Downside: 4.4%

MPL stock view post FY25 Result: 1) Strong 2H25 PH growth \(\sim 2.2\%\) annualised; more in line with industry. Market share gains planned for FY26: MPL is reinvesting for growth into FY26 (both MPL/AHM) through retention, acquisition in priority segments (including corporates). 2) Expenses / MER was higher than expected: Reflecting higher operating expenses for growth; FY26 expected to be driven by inflation \((15\%\) p.a. + M&A 4) Non- resident margin/growth 5) Cyber cost drop off into FY27 6) Strong capital position + APRA capital return opportunity.

Overall comment: Undeniably, the NPAT for 2H25 was very slightly softer than expected driven by Better group insurance margin at \(17.8\%\) vs. consensus of \(17.6\%\) (largely from non- resident business) but this was offset by higher expenses which was slightly above the top end of FY25 guidance of A \(\) 650m\(and lower MPL Health profits. The margin expansion \(\) 1\(\) \ \(\) 1.5\(\) \ \(\) 1.5\(\) \ \(\) 1.5\(with through from resident was in line but driven by better - than - expected risk equalisation outcomes. 2H25 claims inflation improved to 2.1\% vs. 1H25 of 2.3\% with guidance of 2.6\% to 2.9\% for FY26 (based on agreed FY25 indexation against rate of - 4\% for the most part of FY26 suggesting perhaps margin stability into FY26).

1) Underlying NPAT: 2H25 result was a small miss at A \(\) 320.0m\(vs. GSe of A\) \ \(325.2m\) and MPL consensus of A \(\) 329.5m\(. 2) Group operating profit: 2H25 result was a small miss at A\) \ \(402.3m\) vs. GSe of A \(\) 408.9m\(and MPL consensus of A\) \ \(404.6m\) . 3) Dividend in line with MPL's payout ratio: Dividend per share of 10.2cps vs. GSe of 10.0cps (MPL consensus 10.2cps). Payout ratio for 2H25 was \(\sim 88\%\) , FY25 payout ratio was \(80\%\) vs. \(75 - 85\%\) target of underlying NPAT. 4) Health insurance operating profit - broadly in line: 2H25 was at A \(\) 392m\(vs. GSe at A\) \ \(394m\) (MPL consensus A \(\) 392m\(). 5) Medibank Health - slightly softer: 2H25 MPL Health segment profit was weaker than expected at A\) \ \(39.1m\) vs. GSe of A \(\) 43.9m\(and MPL consensus at A\) \ \(42.2m\) . 6) Underlying resident gross margin was in line at \(16.9\%\) for 2H25 vs. GSe of \(16.9\%\) (MPL consensus \(16.9\%\) ). Net margin in line at \(9.5\%\) .

Net resident policyholder growth of \(1.4\%\) for FY25 and aims to grow market share in FY26 (further growth in MPL brand): MPL brand up \(0.3\%\) and AHM up \(4.3\%\) - MPL flags improving momentum over 2H25.
Downgrading quite high, a similar trend to NHF - MPL expects higher downgrading in FY26; customer growth skewed to lower tier products: \(0.9\%\) for FY25 suggesting \(1.3\%\) for 2H25.

Lapse rate improved between 2024 and 2025: MPL's lapse rate improved 20bps over FY25 to \(10.1\%\) . Lapses improved across both Medibank and ahm brands despite higher industry switching rates. The improvement was supported by investment in additional product benefits and the Live Better rewards program.

Claims per policy unit booked at \(2.1\%\) for 2H25 vs. midpoint of assumption at \(2.7\%\) : FY25 hospital claims inflation was \(3.2\%\) , up 80bps vs pcp (driven by higher private hospital indexation and higher NSW bed- rates), whilst extras inflation was \(- 0.6\%\) , down 270bps vs pcp (driven by prior year claims being A \(\) 51.8m\(less than expectations and economic conditions impacting utilisation of some services). MPL expects claims per policy unit growth of \(2.6 - 2.9\%\) over FY26.
Non- resident business: Policyholder growth of \(11.6\%\) in FY25 vs. pcp driven by positive momentum in worker acquisitions, student acquisition was impacted by

lower visa approvals. Gross margin was at \(36.9\%\) for FY25 (+270bps on pcp), reflecting improved worker and visitor margins, partially offset by a drag on student margins from tenure. MPL will invest to grow market share in FY26, particularly in worker and visitor segments.

Medibank Health: 2H25 MPL Health segment profit was weaker than expected at \(A\) 39.1m vs. GSe of \(A\) 43.9m and MPL consensus at \(A\) 42.2m. The result was impacted by growing losses from investment in JV hospitals, which included initial losses from three recently opened hospitals. The performance is expected to improve next year as the portfolio matures.

Gross margin in MPL Health (excluding MyHealth) contracted by 110bps to \(52.8\%\) in FY25 vs. pcp whilst net margin increased 100bps to \(19.1\%\) reflecting improved MER efficiency and operating leverage. Myhealth operating profit was A \(10.5m\) over 2H25 vs. A \(11.6m\) in 2H24. Guidance: MPL continues to target \(>15\%\) per annum organic growth and M&A investment towards the top end of the A \(150m\) to A \(250m\) range over FY24- FY26 (3 years), with \(\sim A\) 59m invested in FY24 and FY25.

MER increasing: MER of \(8.3\%\) in 2H25 vs GSe of \(8.1\%\) (MPL consensus \(8.2\%\) ), impacted by higher operating expenses (for growth) and an increase in D&A from increased investment in digital assets. FY25 management expenses were \(A\) 654.9m, slightly above A \(650m\) guidance, with a stable to modestly improving MER expected over time. A \(10m\) of productivity savings target was achieved during FY25 and MPL expects a further A \(10m\) in productivity savings over FY26.

Cyber security costs expected to persist into FY26: Non- recurring cybercrime costs were A \(39.7m\) over FY25, in line with expectations of \(\sim A\) 40m. A \(35m\) in cybercrime costs expected for FY26 with only litigation costs expected in FY27.

MPL had a pre tax covid reserve of A \(228m\) as at Dec- 24, with a declared giveback of A \(228m\) announced, 2H25 savings of \(\sim A\) 30m were allocated to Live Better give- backs: Based on MPL's commitment to return all permanent claims savings from Covid to customers. However, we note that there was a material increase in the LIC over 1H25 to 2H25.

Capital position strong at PCA ratio of \(1.8x\) and Capital ratio at \(14.0\%\) , above target range of \(10 - 12\%\) (additional capital held to offset APRA supervisory adjustment) and unallocated capital of A \(186.2m\) . MPL remains open to capital management if suitable M&A opportunities do not eventuate and expects to deploy \(\sim A\) 150- 250m between FY24 and FY26 for M&A with opportunity to raise Tier 2 capital as well. We await an update of when MPL's APRA capital over lay of A \(250m\) is removed.

Investment income: for 2H25 was at A \(93.3m\) vs. GSe of A \(90.6m\) (MPL consensus A \(93.3m\) ). Underlying spread to RBA cash rate was 166bps (vs. 150- 200bps spread targeted). MPL expects 25bps rate cuts to impact annualised interest income by A \(7m\) . MPL will consider options including target asset allocation
and defensive asset settings to help offset RBA cash rate impacts.

Resident policyholder growth: MPL aims to gain share from FY26. MPL expects industry growth to moderate in FY26 vs. FY25.

Resident policyholder market share: MPL continues to target Resident policyholder market share growth of 25- 75bps by FY27 on FY24 (Jun- 24 market share was 26.70%, but Jun- 25 market share dropped to 26.46%).

Policyholder giveback / Covid- 19 equity reserve: MPL has finalised the giveback program with the giveback increased to A\$228m from A\$160m. As at Jun- 25, Covid- 19 reserve balance was now fully released.
Claims inflation expectations: MPL now targets claims per policy unit growth of 2.6% to 2.9% for FY26 across resident business (FY25 was 2.2%).
Downgrading: increased in FY25 to 0.9%, expects modestly higher downgrading in FY26.
Expenses: MPL targets a stable to modestly improving MER (was 8.0% over FY25). MPL again guides to A\$10m of productivity savings over FY26 (vs. A\$10m in FY25).

Cybercrime costs: MPL expects cybercrime costs of \~A\$35m for FY26 (FY25 was A\$39.7m) but continues to exclude cost of potential findings or regulatory outcomes or litigations. FY27 costs expected to be largely related to regulatory investigations and litigation.
Medibank Health: MPL continues to target >15% per annum organic growth and M&A investment towards the top end of the A\$150m to A\$250m range over
FY24-FY26 (3 years), with \(\sim\) A\$59m invested in FY24 and FY25. Performance of JVs is expected to improve in FY26 as the portfolio matures.
Dividend payout range of \(75\% - 85\%\) of Underlying NPAT maintained. Non- resident: Will invest to grow market share in FY26, particularly in worker and visitor segments.
Overall, we have made very minor earnings changes; earnings are largely unchanged reflecting MPL's FY26 guidance. We retain our PT of A\$4.80.

MPL is one of the largest private health insurers in Australia. We have a relative Neutral rating on the stock. We like MPL given: 1) It offers defensive exposure to the private health insurance sector 2) The claims environment (utilisation / inflation) has been broadly benign but with evidence of inflation / hospital indexation, 3) policyholder give backs are supporting retention. We are Neutral rated largely reflecting MPL's strong valuation.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
